node.text: Another day chasing light and trying to take some interesting photographs of the completed boxes featured in my next book, Build Better Boxes, which comes out later this year. There will be a limited edition hard cover of the book as well as the soft cover edition.

node.text: I’m at the last stage of making my next book, Build Better Boxes. Today I’ve been taking beauty shots of the completed boxes. It’s been overcast and raining most of the day, which is actually a good thing, because the light is more diffuse than when it’s clear and sunny. Pop the camera on a tripod, slow down the shutter speed, and use bounce cards if necessary. If I had good lights, I would probably use those, but I don’t, so I use the sun instead.

node.text: Well, I’m happy with how this one turned out, at least in terms of the design. It’s what I envisioned. The execution could be better, but there’s always next time. I like the green circle with the green divider visible between the two lids. Tomorrow I’ll post a video that shows how the lids open, because someone asked about pulls yesterday. The cutouts are the pulls, so to speak. There’s a dent in the top of the divider that happened after I painted it. So frustrating. Argh.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Matt Kenney on July 27, 2021.

node.text: This is the box I’ve been making as part of my online box-making course. I designed it on the fly during the first class, when we discussed things like proportions and I then sat down and sketched out ideas live. It was fun. The circle and the divider will both be painted with milk paint. The inside of the bottom gets fabric. By the way, I think the circle looks off-center in the second photo because of the shadow created by the light coming in from the window. It’s actually not off center.

node.text: Back in 2018 I was getting ready to go to Australia for the first time, where I would teach some kumiko. I did not want to take my Nakaya dozuki, because I had ordered it from Japan and was worried that it might not make it through customs. So, I hopped on Amazon and looked for another saw. I found one, ordered it and when it showed up I was surprised and happy to discover that it was the exact same Nakaya saw I already owned. In the US, they are sold under the name Suizan (@suizan_japan). I ended up with a few more of their saws through the years! The saw second from the bottom is the one I use when making kumiko and I own three, taking them when I teach in case a student needs one. They are great saws. I am asked often about which dozuki I recommend, and this is the one. It’s the ultra fine tooth dozuki.

node.text: Here’s a fairly smart way to set the cutting height of a dado set for rabbets. Mark the height on the sacrificial fence, attach the fence to the rip fence, raise the blade to the line, and then cut the rabbets. No need for tedious test cuts and measuring until the blade is at the correct height.

node.text: I do my best to pay attention to details when I am designing and making furniture and boxes. Here are a few things I did for this jewelry box: straight grain harmonizes with rectilinear shapes, it’s super tight grain (looks better than looser grain would on parts this size), dovetail layouts mirror one another on adjoining parts, pulls are smaller for small drawers than they are for bigger drawers, but they have the same radius, the middle spacer between the stand and case is the same width as the vertical divider in the case and the two outer spacers are the same width as the case sides. I like doing this, but it also drives me crazy at times because I can’t escape it. It’s a quirk, I suppose, to be so obsessed with order and detail but I am putting it to good use.

node.text: Here’s how I make small pulls with a curve on the front edge. Mill the cocobolo by hand. Cut to fit into my little circle jig and sand the arc into the pull. Glue it to the drawer. The blue tape locates the pull. Slide the drawer in! Done.

node.text: This jewelry cabinet is just about done. Today I’ll clean it thoroughly and then apply a few coats of shellac and then some wax. Later I’ll post a video showing how I made the pulls.
